**Comparative Review**

The first two systems reviewed in this study represent contrasting approaches to Multi-Agent System design in healthcare. IoT-MAS-T2D, developed by Baroud (2025), is an empirically validated framework targeting Type 2 Diabetes management in older adults, integrating five specialized agents across a three-layer IoT, Edge, and Application architecture. The system collects real-time patient data through wearable devices including Continuous Glucose Monitors, smartwatches, and smart rings, and applies Federated Learning via the FedAvg protocol across ten distributed edge nodes to ensure privacy-preserving model training compliant with GDPR and HIPAA. Its clinical validation through a twelve-month quasi-experimental study involving 200 patients demonstrated a statistically significant HbA1c reduction of 1.3 percent and a diagnostic accuracy of 89.2 percent, making it one of the most empirically robust systems in this comparison. In contrast, HMAS-Sepsis, proposed by Borkowski and Ben-Ari (2025), is an entirely conceptual seven-agent framework designed for sepsis management and hospital workflow optimization. While it proposes technically sophisticated features including Blockchain-based immutable audit trails, HL7 FHIR and SNOMED CT interoperability, and fine-tuned Large Language Models per agent, none of these mechanisms have been empirically tested or validated in a clinical environment. The fundamental distinction between these two systems lies in their evidence maturity — IoT-MAS-T2D delivers measurable, statistically validated clinical outcomes, whereas HMAS-Sepsis, despite its architectural ambition, remains a theoretical blueprint awaiting empirical verification.

The third and fourth systems in this study demonstrate greater architectural sophistication but diverge significantly in their validation strategies and clinical scope. AgentCare, developed by Nimbalkar et al. (2025), is a six-agent, four-layer framework supporting multi-domain disease detection across chronic illness, cancer, emergency care, and mental health. Its architecture incorporates Federated Learning combined with Differential Privacy and Secure Multi-Party Computation, achieving an impressive Area Under the Curve of 0.99 in federated evaluation. However, its validation relies exclusively on the Breast Cancer Wisconsin benchmark dataset — a relatively small and domain-specific dataset — which significantly limits the generalizability of its reported performance metrics. AURELIUS, developed by Chandrasekaran (2025), represents the most technically advanced system in this comparison in terms of reasoning architecture. It employs a hierarchical Bayesian Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning framework with uncertainty quantification, evaluated on 34,000 ICU stays from the MIMIC-IV dataset, achieving an AUROC of 0.952 and a time-to-intervention of 16.7 hours with statistically rigorous validation including Bonferroni correction across five random seeds. Its most distinctive contribution is an uncertainty-aware governance mechanism that selectively escalates clinical decisions to human oversight when the agent's confidence score falls below a defined threshold — establishing a new standard for responsible autonomous decision-making in critical care environments. While AgentCare excels in domain breadth, AURELIUS leads in validation rigor, uncertainty management, and clinical reliability.

The fifth system, EthicMAS-ICU, developed by Chen, Albarqawi, and Chen (2025), makes the most distinctive ethical contribution among all five frameworks reviewed. Built on GPT-4o and comprising seven specialized agents coordinated through a Directed Acyclic Graph pipeline, the system targets ICU mortality prediction and length-of-stay estimation using the eICU database across 150 patients and eight evaluation runs. Its defining innovation is a dedicated Transparency Agent — the only such mechanism in this comparative study — that quantifies explainability, interpretability, and traceability through a formalized scoring system, achieving a transparency score of 85.5 percent. This positions EthicMAS-ICU as the only system in this review that treats ethical governance not as a supplementary consideration but as a core architectural component. Drawing broader conclusions across all five systems, several cross-cutting patterns emerge. Federated Learning is universally adopted as the primary privacy mechanism, yet implementation depth, governance formalization, and audit trail robustness vary considerably across frameworks. Validation maturity remains the most significant differentiator — IoT-MAS-T2D and AURELIUS demonstrate the strongest empirical foundations, AgentCare and EthicMAS-ICU present limited but real evaluations, while HMAS-Sepsis remains entirely unvalidated. Collectively, these five systems highlight both the rapid advancement and the persistent fragmentation of Multi-Agent AI research in healthcare, underscoring the urgent need for standardized evaluation frameworks, multicenter clinical trials, and unified ethical governance standards to guide the responsible deployment of MAS in global healthcare systems.
